  <brief_title>Lactic Acid in the Rectum and Life-Threatening Infection</brief_title>
  <official_title>Does the Concentration of L-Lactate in the Rectum Correlate With Mortality and Morbidity in Patients With Septic Shock?</official_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>Herlev Hospital</agency>
      <agency_class>Other</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>Herlev Hospital</source>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Life-threatening infection impairs bloodflow to the gut, thereby causing less delivery of
      oxygen. This leads to increased formation of lactic acid.

      The investigators hypothesize, that the more serious the condition, the higher the
      concentration of lactic acid will be, thus relating to the risk of multiple organ failure or
      death.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
